"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807150","Department for Education","false","2017-12-20","<p>I am sorry, but the Department for Education does not collect information on whether local authorities contract out their adoption services to third party organisations.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-20T09:37:30.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807150/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807150/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-15","Adoption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which local authorities have contracted out their adoption services to a third party;  and what the name is of each such contractor.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","119798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807151","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-20","<p>The Tailored Review, which we are currently carrying out, is assessing all areas of UK Anti-Doping’s efficiency, effectiveness and governance and how it is preparing for the future.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-12-20T12:05:00.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807151/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807151/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-12-15","UK Anti-doping: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if her Department will take steps to cover the legal costs of UK  Anti-Doping as part of the ongoing tailored review.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","119799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807153","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-20","<p>The Government is committed to addressing penalties for those who are on the poorest value tariffs and the detriment found by the Competition and Markets Authority, which is why we have published the draft Domestic Gas &amp; Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill for pre-legislative scrutiny.</p><p>The Government will also issue a Consumer Green Paper in due course that tackles areas where markets are not working for consumers and businesses.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-12-20T12:46:09.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807153/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807153/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-15","Consumers: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he has any plans to address the loyalty penalty in essential markets.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","119801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807154","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-20","<p>We want markets that work well for all consumers and my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State regularly meets with Ofgem and other regulators to discuss a range of consumer issues.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-12-20T12:45:16.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807154/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807154/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-15","Consumers: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with regulators on the loyalty penalty faced by consumers who don't switch provider.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","119802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807155","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-20","<p>My department does not hold a list of funding requests received by Manchester City Council.</p><p> </p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-12-20T17:16:25.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807155/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807155/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-15","Terrorism: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 12 December 2017 to Question 118073, if he will list the requests received by Manchester City Council.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","119803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807156","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-20","<p>In its Price Review 2019 methodology (<a href="https://www.ofwat.gov.uk/regulated-companies/price-review/2019-price-review-final-methodology/" target="_blank">https://www.ofwat.gov.uk/regulated-companies/price-review/2019-price-review-final-methodology/</a>), Ofwat is challenging companies to commit to achieving at least a 15% reduction in leakage, and to provide a clear explanation where they cannot achieve such a reduction. Companies will need to be both efficient and innovative in addressing leaks in their network. The specific technologies chosen by the companies to detect and manage leaks is a matter for them.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-20T17:31:36.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807156/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807156/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-15","Water Supply: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 11 December 2017 to Question 117510, what discussions his Department has had with Ofwat to ensure that water and sewerage companies adopt the latest technology in leakage detection and that such technology provides value for money.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","119804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807157","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-20","<p>The Personal Independence Payments (PIP) Assessment Guidance has been updated to reflect changes in how the Department considers whether an activity can be performed ‘safely’ and whether supervision is required.</p><p>The criteria that will be followed in the Legal Entitlements and Administrative Practices exercise to review awards of PIP is set out in in this guidance.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-12-20T16:09:22.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807157/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807157/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-15","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's publication ADM Memo 30/17, if he will publish the criteria used in the LEAP exercise to review awards of personal independent payment claimants who may be affected by the updated PIP Assessment Guidance detailed in the Written Statement of 2 November 2017, HCWS218.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","119805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807158","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-20","<p>Anyone in payment, or who has had a decision since 9 March, will be covered by the Legal Entitlements and Administrative Practices (LEAP) exercise.</p><p> </p><p>The judgment only affects entitlement from the 9 March.</p><p> </p><p>In line with legislation, anyone who was disallowed before 9 March would need to re-apply.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-12-20T16:07:49.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807158/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807158/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-15","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Written Statement of 2 November 2017, HCWS218, whether previous personal independence payment applicants who may benefit from the update to PIP Assessment Guidance but whose applications were unsuccessful before 9 March 2017 should (a) reapply for PIP, (b) await contact from his Department regarding their claims or (c) request a review of their initial claim in light of the updated guidance.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","119806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807159","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-21","<p>In line with our existing programme of continuous improvement we have recently made changes to the PIP Assessment Guide in relation to safety and supervision which may impact on those with conditions which affect consciousness such as epilepsy.</p><p> </p><p>Personal Independence Payment (PIP) is more modern, dynamic and fair than its predecessor, Disability Living Allowance (DLA), and focuses support on those experiencing the greatest barriers to living independently. As PIP is a different benefit to DLA with different assessment criteria, we would expect to see some variation between outcomes for different disabling conditions. Additionally, many DLA claimants have not undergone any kind of assessment of their needs for several years and their condition, treatment or therapy and needs arising from their condition may have changed substantially.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-12-21T14:03:06.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807159/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807159/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-15","Personal Independence Payment: Epilepsy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to table 8D of the Personal Independence Payment: DLA to PIP reassessment outcomes, October 2017, what steps his Department is taking to address the disproportionate number of people with epilepsy who have seen their awards refused or reduced during the transition to personal independence payments; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","119807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807160","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-27","<p>The Ministry of Justice carried out a call for evidence on corporate criminal liability for economic crime in 2017, to establish whether further reform of the law was necessary. The response will issue in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","119809","2017-12-27T15:20:51.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807160/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807160/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-15","Fraud: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make it his policy for there to be a review of the options for law reform to ensure that large companies and financial institutions can be prosecuted for economic crime in the UK.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","119808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807161","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-27","<p>The Ministry of Justice carried out a call for evidence on corporate criminal liability for economic crime in 2017, to establish whether further reform of the law was necessary. The response will issue in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","119808","2017-12-27T15:20:51.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807161/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807161/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-15","Companies: Criminal Liability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to publish a call for evidence on the need for legal reform to extend corporate criminal liability beyond bribery and tax evasion.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","119809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807162","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-20","<p>On 11 December the Government published its new Anti-Corruption Strategy. In the Strategy we have committed to publish a draft bill in this session of Parliament for the establishment of a public register of beneficial ownership of overseas legal entities.</p><p> </p><p>The Department ran a call for evidence on this policy earlier in 2017. We will publish a response to the call for evidence early in 2018 and will also set out more detail on the timeline for publishing the legislation.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-12-20T12:49:17.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807162/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807162/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-15","Foreign Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when she plans to create a public register showing the beneficial owners of overseas legal entities which (a) own or buy property in the UK and (b) secure contracts from central Government.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","119810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807163","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-27","<p>​At the Joint Ministerial Council on 28-29 November, the Minister for the Overseas Territories (OTs), Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon, and leaders of the OTs welcomed progress made by those OTs with financial services centres in implementing the arrangements set out in the Exchange of Notes on exchange of beneficia<strong>l</strong> ownership information. They committed, where not already achieved, to expedite work to ensure that the new systems were fully operational and populated.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-12-27T15:27:53.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807163/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807163/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-15","British Overseas Territories: Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in the UK Overseas Territories on the adoption of public registers of beneficial ownership in the UK Overseas Territories.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","119811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807164","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-22","<p>The Government supports the Open Ownership initiative to establish a global online register of company beneficial ownership and through this supports six countries, including Kenya and Ukraine, to set up their own public registers.</p><p>My Department also supports the Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative to work with 14 DFID partner countries to make public the beneficial owners of companies which win oil, gas and mining contracts, by 2020.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-22T13:57:58.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807164/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807164/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-12-15","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what measures she is taking to promote the adoption of public registers of beneficial ownership in other countries.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","119812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807165","Home Office","false","2017-12-21","<p>The UK has been recognised as a country which actively enforces the OECD Convention on Combating Bribery of Foreign Public Officials in International Business Transactions (the “OECD Anti-Bribery Convention”).</p><p>The UK Anti-Corruption Strategy was published on December 11 and contains a clear commitment to promote international implementation of the OECD Anti Bribery Convention, together with other international standards. The Joint Anti-Corruption Unit in the Home Office is working closely with the FCO, DFID, HMT and law enforcement agencies to this end.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-12-21T16:36:31.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807165/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807165/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-15","Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with the Foreign Secretary on the active enforcement of the OECD Anti Bribery Convention.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","119813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807166","Home Office","false","2017-12-22","<p>The Home Office published the UK’s Anti-Corruption Strategy on the 11th December, which establishes an ambitious longer-term framework to guide UK government efforts to tackle corruption at home and abroad in the period to 2022. It sets out priorities for the government's anti-corruption response and includes a strong recognition of the relationship of integrity in business and prosperity. <br> <br>As part of this, the Department for International Trade will consider how anti-corruption can be best supported through our bilateral and regional trade dialogues and trading agreements as the UK develops its position as an independent trading nation. The Home Office is overseeing implementation of the Anti-Corruption Strategy and as part of this is working closely with the Department for International Trade. <br></p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-12-22T10:49:59.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807166/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807166/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-15","Corruption: Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for International Trade on the promotion of anti-corruption measures through bilateral trade deals.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","119814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807167","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-22","<p>Combatting the illegal wildlife trade (IWT) is a priority for the UK Government. This is why we are investing £26 million globally, and working with international partners, to tackle the systemic issues driving IWT.</p><p> </p><p>Our work to combat IWT involves a number of multilateral and bilateral initiatives, including the commitments we made at the Hanoi Illegal Wildlife Trade Conference: http://www.parliament.uk/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2016-12-01/HCWS295</p><p> </p><p>These commitments complement our existing initiatives, such as funding our Illegal Wildlife Trade Challenge Fund, which aims to reduce demand, strengthen enforcement, ensure effective legal frameworks and develop sustainable livelihoods for communities affected by IWT. A list of projects can be found on the IWT Challenge Fund website: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/illegal-wildlife-trade-iwt-challenge-fund" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/Government/collections/illegal-wildlife-trade-iwt-challenge-fund</a></p><p> </p><p>Following the success of the inaugural international conference on IWT in London in 2014 and UK Government support for the subsequent successful conferences in Kasane (2015) and Hanoi (2016), the UK will bring global leaders back to London in October 2018 for a fourth high level international meeting. This meeting will make sure that IWT stays at the top of the political agenda, that all participants deliver on existing commitments and instigate new partnerships for action.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-22T13:33:45.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807167/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807167/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-15","Wildlife: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what (a) multilateral and (b) bilateral initiatives he has taken to counter the illegal wildlife trade.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","119815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807168","Home Office","false","2017-12-22","<p>The Home Office does not have access to operational details of requests made by UK law enforcement authorities for beneficial ownership information.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-12-22T10:46:19.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807168/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807168/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-15","British Overseas Territories: Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 14 December 2017 to Question 117953,  whether her Department has access to operational details of requests made by UK law enforcement authorities for beneficial ownership information.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","119816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807169","Home Office","false","2017-12-20","<p>Fees for firearm and shotgun licences issued by the police remain under review. These were last increased in 2015 to enable police forces to achieve full cost recovery when a new online licensing system becomes operational. Work is continuing on this, including whether improvements can be made to the existing IT system. We are not proposing to make changes to the fees until further progress has been made on this.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-12-20T15:45:07.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807169/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807169/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-15","Firearms: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 8 September 2017 to Question 6341, when she expects to make a decision on fees for firearm and shotgun licences administered by the police.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","119817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807170","Scotland Office","false","2017-12-20","<p>The Scotland Office has worked with the following external advisers/companies for advertising in each of the last four years. These companies were procured through standard Crown Commercial procedure.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>Nil</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>Nil</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p>Nil</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td><td><p>The Leith Agency, Carat Ltd.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-12-20T11:18:24.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807170/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807170/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-12-15","Scotland Office: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 6 September 2017 to Question 6287, what external advisers or companies his Department has used for advertising in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","119818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807171","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-30","<p>There are no powers to confiscate the property of a person who is street homeless on the basis that they are sleeping rough.</p><p> </p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-01-30T15:48:09.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807171/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/807171/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-15","Homelessness: Personal Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, under what powers the property of a person who is street homeless can be confiscated.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","119819"
